About
Closed on Thursdays! The famous painter Caravaggio (1573-1610) was commissioned to paint for this church, where in one of its chapels is his realistic naturalism in three scenes of the life of St. Matthew.

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Navona / Pantheon / Campo de Fiori
With three of Romes most beloved piazzas within a five-minute walk of each other, the Navona / Pantheon / Campo area may be the prettiest and most picturesque area of the city. Join the beautiful throngs hanging out in cafes, boutiques, art galleries, and wine bars, or peek at a neighborhood museum or monument. If you want nonstop movida, the streets here are busy with chic bicyclists and Vespa drivers, street vendors, merchants, and locals. There is no rhyme or reason to its winding streets and there's something to see around every corner, so take pleasure in a spontaneous wander.

    Coin operated light for Caravaggio's masterpieces
    No, the 4 stars is not for my favorite painter, Caravaggio, and yes, the Matthew's cycle is simply amazing. The deduction is for the most stupid idea to install a coin operated light at the Matthew chapel. We were there with a crowd marveling at the paintings, and suddenly, it all went dark! We were all scratching our heads. After some time, the chief husher (yes, he kept hushing the patrons) came to point us to the box on the side. Of course, as on cue it malfunctioned and he had to open the box and turned it back on. Again. What a stupid idea! You want to make money out of the paintings, sure, charge us! Don't install a stupid box that takes one Euro at a time for 60 seconds of light, and more over, not making it clear anyone that's how we can see these masterpieces. Unfortunately, down the road the Church of Augustines is doing the same thing with the Madonna of Loreto.

    The Church of St. Louis of the French is a Catholic church located near Piazza Navona in Rome. The church is dedicated to the patron saints of France: Virgin Mary, Dionysius the Areopagite and King Louis IX of France. The church was built between 1518 and 1589.

    Hong Kong, China177,757 contributions
    Caravaggio Life of St. Matthew Cycle masterpieces
    The Church of St. Louis of the French (San Luigi dei Francesi) is located at the public square by the same name around halfway between Piazza Navona and Piazza Della Rotonda where you find the Pantheon. It is open from 9.30am to 12.45pm and 2.30pm to 6.30pm daily. This is the national church for French citizens living in Rome. It was designed by Giacomo della Porta and completed in 1589 by Domenico Fontana. The facade is tiered with niches fitted with statues of French national heroes. What most come here to see how is the ornate Baroque interior and in particular the Contarelli Chapel which contains three masterpiece cycle by Caravaggio known as the Life of St. Matthew (1599-1600). These are the world famous 'The Calling', 'The Inspiration' and The Martydom' of St. Matthew. Expect a small crowd of art lovers and curious other tourists most of the time at this particular chapel. There is a coin operating machine which is fairly regularly fed by tourists wishing to illuminate the masterpieces so that nice pictures can be taken. Beyond the Caravaggio paintings, the works in other chapels are heavily decorated and fairly nice to view as well. The nave itself is adorned with ornamentation, lots of gilding and a good ceiling fresco. These may be overlooked because of the heavy focus on the Contarelli Chapel but are worth a few minutes of your time as well.
    Visited March 2024
    Traveled with family
    Written April 28, 2024

Vadim
Murmansk, Russia35,009 contributions
Where to see Caravaggio in Rome?
Jun 2023 Solo
The great revolutionary in painting, the founder of Chiaroscuro technique, spent the most creative years of his short 39-year life in Rome, leaving many of his paintings in private collections and churches here. The most representative is the Borghese Gallery. There are most of the master's paintings here- 6: David with the Head of Goliath, A boy and a fruit basket, a Sick Bacchus, Madonna and Child with St. Anne, St. John the Baptist, St. Jerome in meditation. However, the Borghese Gallery is the most difficult to access. You can only get into it by online reservation, and I can't do it on a visit to Rome. Another option is to use one ticket to see two first-class paintings by the master - Judith killing Holofernes and Narcissus in the Palazzo Barberini, and with the same ticket you can get to the Corsini Gallery in Trastevere, where you can see another version of John the Baptist. Caravaggio loved to paint pictures on the same subject. Strangely enough, the great museums of Rome have only one painting by the painter: the Capitoline Museums are a Fortune Teller or Fortune Teller, and the Vatican Pinacoteca is the Burial of Christ. Another painting in the Palazzo Dora Pamphili (a specific Penitent Magdalene) and the Odescalchi-Balbi Gallery (The Conversion of Saul). All of the above galleries are paid, and some have expensive tickets. However, Rome is an amazing city. Here you can watch Caravaggio for free. The theme of the same Saul in the church of Santa Maria del Popolo. The Conversion of Saul or Paul on the Way to Damascus and the Crucifixion of St. Peter. In the church of San Agostino, you can see the Madonna di Loreto or the Mother of Pilgrims. And finally, there are three Caravaggio paintings here in San Luigi Francesi:
The Calling of Saint Matthew The Inspiration of Saint Matthew, and The Martyrdom of Saint Matthew. Having previously seen Caravaggio in the Capitoline Museums, the Vatican Pinacoteca, Palazzo Barberini and Santa Maria del Popolo, I hoped to see the series and Matthew here. However, the church was closing. They let me see the nave, but they didn't let me see Caravaggio anymore. The Gestalt is not closed. Although the church itself is not bad. An example of Counter-Reformation art: multicolored marble, geometrically complex, gilded stucco, painted ceiling lights. The ceiling was painted in 1754 by the French painter Natoire on the theme "The Death and Glory of Saint Louis", to which the church is dedicated. Louis IX, as you know, died in Tunisia, where the last eighth crusade went. The cause of death is not heroic at all - dysentery. The whole church is very French. Everything is here for the glory of France. From the ceiling light to the numerous tombs. At one time, Pope Leo X made a concession to the French community, making it an extraterritorial parish for all French expatriates. This meant that for any Frenchman in and around Rome, the church was his own parish. In turn, this meant that the French did not have to pay or receive the privilege of being buried in San Luigi Francesi. The shaft of burials was stopped only by the physical size of the church. Cardinals are buried here (well, it's everywhere), the mistress of the gloomy thinker Chateaubriand, the economist Frederic Bastiat, the painter Claude Lorrain. The main altar is decorated with a painting by Francesco Bassano Jr. Madonna Assunta (Ascension of the Virgin). In addition to the Contarelli Chapel with three paintings by Caravaggio, until the 1950s, when Caravaggio came into fashion, the most valuable painting in San Luigi Francesi was considered Domenichino's painting in the Chapel of St. Cecilia. In the same chapel on the altar there is a painting "Ecstasy of Saint Cecilia", which can be mistaken for Raphael. However, it is a copy of the famous artist Guido Reni.
Written May 26, 2024

As others have already said, the church is free to visit. I would recommend attending a Mass to see the church at its best, as they light it well then. Again, to illuminate the Carravagios, there is a 1e charge slot. However, it's easy to wait and have others pay to illuminate it first (since there's usually a small crowd gathered around), so you won't have to pay anything at all! Most of the Caravaggios are free to see in the city. I would recommend visiting Santa Maria del Popolo to see more of his famous works for free.
